The instability value at index $i$ is defined as:
$\text{Instability}(i) = \max(nums[0..i]) - \min(nums[i..n-1])$

Where:
1. $\max(nums[0..i])$ is the maximum element in the prefix $nums[0]$ through $nums[i]$.
2. $\min(nums[i..n-1])$ is the minimum element in the suffix $nums[i]$ through $nums[n-1]$.

We need to iterate from $i=0$ to $n-1$, calculate the instability value for each $i$, and return the first $i$ where $\text{Instability}(i) \le k$. If no such $i$ exists, we return $-1$.

The constraints are small: $N \le 100$. This suggests that an $O(N^2)$ or even $O(N^3)$ solution might pass, but an $O(N)$ solution is preferable and easily achievable.

Let $N$ be the length of `nums`.

We need two pieces of information for each $i$:
1. Prefix Maximum up to $i$: $\text{MaxPrefix}[i] = \max(nums[0], \dots, nums[i])$.
2. Suffix Minimum from $i$: $\text{MinSuffix}[i] = \min(nums[i], \dots, nums[N-1])$.

If we precalculate these two arrays, we can find the instability value for any $i$ in $O(1)$.

### Step 1: Calculate Prefix Maximums

We can calculate $\text{MaxPrefix}$ in $O(N)$ time.

$\text{MaxPrefix}[0] = nums[0]$
$\text{MaxPrefix}[i] = \max(\text{MaxPrefix}[i-1], nums[i])$ for $i > 0$.

### Step 2: Calculate Suffix Minimums

We can calculate $\text{MinSuffix}$ in $O(N)$ time, iterating backwards.

$\text{MinSuffix}[N-1] = nums[N-1]$
$\text{MinSuffix}[i] = \min(\text{MinSuffix}[i+1], nums[i])$ for $i < N-1$.

### Step 3: Find the Smallest Stable Index

Iterate $i$ from $0$ to $N-1$.
Calculate $\text{Instability}(i) = \text{MaxPrefix}[i] - \text{MinSuffix}[i]$.
If $\text{Instability}(i) \le k$, return $i$.

If the loop finishes without finding such an $i$, return $-1$.

The overall time complexity will be $O(N) + O(N) + O(N) = O(N)$, which is very fast given $N \le 100$.

